piratory tract (nasal turbinate and trachea) maintained at an air interface. These air interface respiratory organ cultures provide a physiological infection environment for the study of M. haemolytica pathogenesis: the full complement of host epithelial cells are present; the epithelium is maintained in air, rather than in submerged culture; epithelial physical defenses are intact and microbes must interact with the muco-ciliary system in order to successfully colonise; and the host response, characterized by increased mucus production, resembles that seen in vivo. The new infection model utilizes abattoir material and so addresses the 3Rs. 



The air interface cultures are robust and remain in an overall physiologically-intact state for 48 h (bovine) and 72 h (ovine cultures) in culture. The models provide a reproducible infection model for virulent ovine and bovine isolates of M. haemolytica and show inoculum-dependent colonization and host response. The models show differences in regional colonization ability of M. haemolytica with greater colonization of nasal tissue than trachea and an associated greater host response to infection in nasal tissue compared to trachea.



In summary, the air interface models developed in phase 1 provide a suitable model for studying M. haemolytica adhesion and colonisation for use in the Glasgow phase of the project (phases 2 and 3). Furthermore, the models are likely to be applicable to other bacterial and viral respiratory pathogens and to be useful to other researchers working in the field of respiratory microbial pathogenesis.</gtr:description><gtr:id>A5D1DCA8-19F2-4E0D-9AA2-E2F8BCDE8C9A</gtr:id><gtr:impact>This phase of the project showed that ex vivo explants of respiratory epithelium could be maintained as air interface organ cultures. Although the data generated in this phase of the project suggested that the models could be used for the study of interactions between explants and Mannheimia sp, subsequent rigorous assessment of the models by the Glasgow research group did not support these observations. As a result, an alternative model using dispersed bronchial epithelial cells was successfully used by the Glasgow group to study the interaction of Mannhemia with airway epithelial cells.</gtr:impact><gtr:outcomeId>r-9781477004.086113c6b5a230</gtr:outcomeId><gtr:providedToOthers>true</gtr:providedToOthers><gtr:title>In vitro infection model for M. haemolytica</gtr:title><gtr:type>Cell line</gtr:type><gtr:yearFirstProvided>2009</gtr:yearFirstProvided></gtr:researchMaterialOutput></gtr:researchMaterialOutputs><gtr:softwareAndTechnicalProductOutputs/><gtr:spinOutOutputs/></gtr:output><gtr:publications><gtr:publication><gtr:id>69EE7BD1-967D-41D8-86D6-E9772B1ACFF8</gtr:id><gtr:title>International Pasteurellaceae Society Conference - abstract 2</gtr:title><gtr:authors><gtr:author url="http://gtr.ukri.org:80/person/8f503c68f45b18bcbc6354556da676e8"><gtr:id>8f503c68f45b18bcbc6354556da676e8</gtr:id><gtr:otherNames>Jonathan D A Hounsome (Author)</gtr:otherNames></gtr:author></gtr:authors><gtr:date>2008-01-01</gtr:date><gtr:outcomeId>m_9502489728140d3f86</gtr:outcomeId></gtr:publication><gtr:publication>